Tools.Description:
Render structured information as a visual card instead of plain text. Use for invoices, profiles, reports, comparisons, or any data benefiting from visual hierarchy over a wall-of-text.

ROOT STRUCTURE (mandatory): {"title": "string (required)", "subtitle": "string (optional)", "components": [array of component objects (required)]}. Root MUST have 'title' and 'components' — NEVER 'sections', 'data', or any other wrapper.

COMPONENT DICTIONARY — 8 types. Every component's 'type' must be its FIRST property and match one of these exactly:

1. text_block — narrative prose (explanations, warnings, notes) that isn't a labeled field. Properties: content (required), style: normal|bold|muted|small (default normal). Not for labeled data (key_value), lists (list), or single-word tags (badge). Ex: {"type": "text_block", "content": "⚠️ Payment is 53 days overdue.", "style": "bold"}

2. key_value — one labeled field. Properties: key (required), value (required), emphasize: boolean (default false). Ex: {"type": "key_value", "key": "Due Date", "value": "15/12/2025", "emphasize": true}

3. divider — plain horizontal separator between distinct sections. No properties; don't overuse. Ex: {"type": "divider"}

4. list — an enumeration of related items. Properties: items: array of strings (required), style: bullet|numbered|plain (default bullet — numbered when order matters, plain for a compact listing). Not for labeled key-value pairs (use key_value/grid). Ex: {"type": "list", "items": ["Premium Plan: €90.00", "Installation Fee: €35.00"], "style": "bullet"}

5. section — nestable heading + child components, for hierarchy. Properties: title (required), subtitle (optional), components: array (required). Max depth: 3 section levels from root. Ex: {"type": "section", "title": "Billing Details", "components": [{"type": "key_value", "key": "Period", "value": "October 2025"}]}

6. grid — compact multi-column key-value layout for ≥2 homogeneous, RELATED fields. Properties: columns: integer 2-4 (required), items: array of {key,value} objects (required). Not for heterogeneous or nested content. Ex: {"type": "grid", "columns": 2, "items": [{"key": "Name", "value": "Mario"}, {"key": "City", "value": "Rome"}]}

7. badge — a short status/category tag. Properties: text (required), variant: success|warning|error|info|neutral (default neutral). success=positive (Paid/Active), warning=attention (Pending/Due Soon), error=negative (Overdue/Failed), info=informational (New/Draft). Ex: {"type": "badge", "text": "Overdue", "variant": "error"}

8. image — an image from URL with optional caption. Properties: src (required, HTTPS), alt (recommended), caption (optional), size: small|medium|large|full (default medium; 200/400/600px or 100% width). Use when visual content aids comprehension, not decoratively, and never as a substitute for a markdown link. Ex: {"type": "image", "src": "https://example.com/avatar.jpg", "alt": "User avatar", "size": "small"}

CRITICAL RULES: (1) root MUST have 'title'+'components', never other wrappers; (2) every component's 'type' is its FIRST property and must match one of the 8 types above exactly; (3) group related content with 'section', max 50 components total, max nesting depth 3; (4) serialize the whole structure to a JSON string before calling; (5) when tool output includes an image URL, use the 'image' component, never a markdown link.

WORKED EXAMPLE (invoice with sections): {"title": "Invoice INV-2025-001", "subtitle": "Due 15/12/2025", "components": [{"type": "section", "title": "Billing Details", "components": [{"type": "key_value", "key": "Customer", "value": "[Company Name]"}, {"type": "key_value", "key": "Status", "value": "Pending", "emphasize": true}]}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "section", "title": "Line Items", "components": [{"type": "list", "items": ["Premium Plan: €90.00", "Installation Fee: €35.00"], "style": "bullet"}]}, {"type": "key_value", "key": "TOTAL", "value": "€130.00", "emphasize": true}, {"type": "badge", "text": "Payment Overdue", "variant": "warning"}]}

JSON WELL-FORMEDNESS (mandatory, non-negotiable): the string must be strictly valid JSON that parses on the first attempt — a malformed payload is silently dropped and the user sees nothing. Before emitting: every '{'/'[' closed by a matching '}'/']' in the correct order; every string in double quotes (never single), internal quotes escaped as \"; commas between siblings but never trailing; property names always quoted; no comments, no ellipsis, no truncation. If uncertain whether the JSON is complete, SIMPLIFY the card (fewer components, shorter strings) rather than risk an unclosed brace — a smaller valid card beats a richer invalid one.
